commit.message:
freebsd: add 32-bit arm support

Our 32-bit arm platform takes four arguments in registers r0 - r3,
followed by arguments pushed to the stack.  The syscall number is
stashed in r7, and we need to be sensitive about whether we're looking
at thumb instructions or not before we rewind pc too far.

Signed-off-by: Kyle Evans <kevans@FreeBSD.org>

freebsd: add support for spilling syscall args to the stack

armv7 and powerpc both stash some number of arguments on the stack.  The
next commit will add armv7 support, so let's get the syscall setup
hashed out.

Stack args in the personality are indicated by having an offset above
the size of `struct reg`.  By convention, these should just use ~0UL
rather than sizeof(struct reg) + X to avoid issues if the struct reg
ABI changes.

There's a bit of a kludge here described in detail in the comments, but
the short version is that mmap's final argument is a 64-bit argument
that should be passed in as a pair of 32-bit ints.  We know the upper 32
bits will always be 0 because we don't use the offset argument, so we
just pad out to four arguments on the stack, with the excess being '0'.

Signed-off-by: Kyle Evans <kevans@FreeBSD.org>

freebsd: remove return value from arch_set_syscall()

On all of FreeBSD's platforms, the syscall number is simply
saved/restored in a register.  Setting it cannot fail, so just remove
the return value from arch_set_syscall().

Signed-off-by: Kyle Evans <kevans@FreeBSD.org>

freebsd: cleanup some effectively dead code

On all platforms (supported or not), the syscall number is stored in a
register, so we don't need to do anything funky to save/restore it in
particular.  Remove arch_save_syscall()/arch_restore_syscall() entirely
from the FreeBSD support.

Signed-off-by: Kyle Evans <kevans@FreeBSD.org>

commit.message:
freebsd: add support for aarch64

Fairly straightforward; args passed in x0 - x5, syscall number
is stashed in x8; x0/x1 used for return values.

Signed-off-by: Kyle Evans <kevans@FreeBSD.org>

freebsd: abstract away details of setting syscall number

On x86, we use eax/rax which also happens to be the same register
used for the return value.  On other architectures, the same
pattern won't necessarily apply.

Signed-off-by: Kyle Evans <kevans@FreeBSD.org>

cirrus: chase supported/default versions

FreeBSD 12.2 is long EoL, 12.4 is the latest and final release of the
stable/12 branch.  Python 3.9 has since been made the default Python,
so let's switch to that.

TIOCNOTTY support landed in 12.2, so we can do the basic test in CI
now.

Signed-off-by: Kyle Evans <kevans@FreeBSD.org>

commit.message: Update FreeBSD build for python3.8 transition

Prefer direct socket syscall APIs over `socketcall`

x86-32 requires the use of the `socketcall` syscall to access the socket
syscall interface, and the logic for handling `socketcall` assumes a
32-bit architecture. However, powerpc provides both the `socket` and
`socketcall` syscalls. The previous logic caused us to prefer
`socketcall` over `socket`, which ended poorly since powerpc is not a
32-bit architecture.

This reverses the order of precedence - we'll always use `socket` if
it's available, and only fall back to `socketcall` if it's not.

Correct return value register for powerpc

The powerpc calling convention is to put the syscall return value in r3,
but ptrace moves it to the `result` struct member.
